<header class="lesson-title">
  <div class="course">PAD 5701 · Quantitative Analysis in Public Administration</div>
  <h1>Week 4 Interactive Lesson: The Normal Curve</h1>
</header>

<div class="lesson-frame">
  <p>Understanding the normal curve is the foundation for the rest of this course. Almost everything in inferential statistics, including confidence intervals (Week 6) and hypothesis tests (Weeks 7 and beyond), depends on normal-curve reasoning. This week builds the conceptual machinery the rest of the semester will use.</p>
</div>

<!-- =========================================
     STEP 1: NORMAL CURVE AS A MODEL + ETYMOLOGY
========================================= -->
<section class="step">
  <div class="step-header">
    <span class="step-number">1</span>
    <h2>The normal curve as a model</h2>
  </div>
  <p>The normal curve is a mathematical model, not the data itself. It is an idealized, smooth, symmetric, bell-shaped curve. Real data may approximate this shape closely, somewhat, or not at all. When real data approximates the shape, the normal curve becomes a useful tool for reasoning about how unusual specific values are.</p>
  <p>Every normal curve shares the same fundamental properties: it is symmetric, has a single peak in the middle (where the mean, median, and mode coincide), and its tails extend outward in both directions without ever quite touching the x-axis. The total area under any normal curve equals 1.00, or 100% of the data.</p>
  <p>What changes from one normal curve to another is only the position of the center and the width of the spread. The mean fixes the position (where the peak sits on the x-axis), and the standard deviation fixes the spread (how wide or narrow the bell is). Two numbers, the mean and the standard deviation, fully describe any specific normal curve.</p>
  
  <h3 style="color: var(--dark-blue); font-size: 17px; margin-top: 20px;">Why "normal"?</h3>
  <p>The curve is called the <em>normal</em> curve, though the exact origin of the term is debated. The most common explanation is that many naturally occurring measurements (heights, blood pressure, errors in physical experiments) tend to follow this bell shape closely enough that early statisticians treated it as the typical or expected distribution. Karl Pearson, one of the term's most influential popularizers, later wrote that he regretted the choice because it implied other distributions were <em>abnormal</em>, which was never the intent. Whatever its precise origin, "normal" does not mean "good" or "right" or "typical" in any value-laden sense. It just means this bell shape happens to appear often enough in measurement contexts that statisticians named it.</p>
</section>

<!-- =========================================
     STEP 2: MEAN, SD, Z-SCORES (with interactive)
========================================= -->
<section class="step">
  <div class="step-header">
    <span class="step-number">2</span>
    <h2>Mean, SD, and Z-scores</h2>
  </div>
  <p>Two numbers fully determine any normal curve. The mean determines where the curve sits on the horizontal axis. The standard deviation sets how wide the bell is.</p>
  <p>Use the controls below to explore how changing either or both of these numbers affects a normal curve directly. Slide the mean to move the curve left or right. Slide the SD to make the bell wider or narrower. The numeric inputs let you type specific values if you want to test something exact.</p>
  
  <div class="curve-widget">
    <h3>Build your own normal curve</h3>
    <p class="subtitle">Adjust the mean and SD to see how the curve repositions and reshapes. The gold reference markers show ±1 SD and ±2 SD from the current mean.</p>
    
    <div class="viz">
      <svg id="interactive-curve-svg" viewBox="0 0 700 280" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"></svg>
    </div>
    
    <div class="ctrl-row">
      <label for="ic-mean-slider">Mean (days):</label>
      <input type="range" id="ic-mean-slider" min="0" max="18" step="0.1" value="6.53">
      <input type="number" id="ic-mean-input" min="0" max="18" step="0.1" value="6.53">
    </div>
    <div class="ctrl-row">
      <label for="ic-sd-slider">SD (days):</label>
      <input type="range" id="ic-sd-slider" min="0.5" max="6" step="0.1" value="3.66">
      <input type="number" id="ic-sd-input" min="0.5" max="6" step="0.1" value="3.66">
    </div>
    
    <div class="preset-row">
      <span class="preset-label">Quick-set to:</span>
      <button class="preset-chip" data-mean="6.53" data-sd="3.66">Full pilot sample</button>
      <button class="preset-chip" data-mean="5.04" data-sd="2.75">Treatment subgroup</button>
      <button class="preset-chip" data-mean="8.01" data-sd="3.86">Control subgroup</button>
      <button class="preset-chip" data-mean="9" data-sd="1">Narrow, centered at 9</button>
      <button class="preset-chip" data-mean="9" data-sd="4">Wide, centered at 9</button>
    </div>
  </div>
  
  <h3 style="color: var(--dark-blue); font-size: 17px; margin-top: 24px;">Z-scores: standardization on the curve</h3>
  <p>A Z-score tells you how many standard deviations a raw value sits from the mean. The formula:</p>
  
  <div class="formula">
    <strong>Z</strong> = (<em>X</em><sub>i</sub> − <span class="xbar">X</span>) / <em>s</em>
  </div>
  
  <p>Where <em>X</em><sub>i</sub> is the raw value (any data point), <span class="xbar">X</span> is the sample mean, and <em>s</em> is the sample standard deviation.</p>
  <p>The Z-score replaces a raw value with a position. Whatever the original scale (dollars, percentages, days, scores), the Z-score expresses how unusual the value is in standard-deviation units. Z = 0 sits at the mean. Z = +1 sits one SD above the mean. Z = −2 sits two SDs below.</p>
  <p>This is the move that lets you compare values across measurements that use completely different scales. A state's vaccination rate (a percentage), its per-pupil school spending (dollars), and its child poverty rate (a different percentage) are all measured on different scales. Raw values cannot be compared directly. Z-scores can, because they put every measurement on the same "how unusual is this" scale.</p>
</section>
  
  <h3 style="color: var(--dark-blue); font-size: 17px; margin-top: 20px;">The empirical rule (68-95-99.7)</h3>
  <p>Because every normal curve has the same shape, the same proportion of the data always falls within the same Z-distance from the mean. Three reference values are worth memorizing:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>About <strong>68%</strong> of the data falls within ±1 SD of the mean (between Z = −1 and Z = +1).</li>
    <li>About <strong>95%</strong> of the data falls within ±2 SD of the mean (between Z = −2 and Z = +2).</li>
    <li>About <strong>99.7%</strong> of the data falls within ±3 SD of the mean (between Z = −3 and Z = +3).</li>
  </ul>
  <p>This is called the <strong>empirical rule</strong> (also known as the 68-95-99.7 rule). Once you know your data is approximately normal and you know the mean and SD, you can immediately characterize any value's position within the distribution.</p>
  
  <div class="callout">
    <div class="callout-label">Shape vs. scale</div>
    <p style="margin: 0;">The 68-95-99.7 percentages are properties of the <em>shape</em> of any normal curve. They hold regardless of what the specific mean and standard deviation are. Whether your data are days absent in the childcare pilot (mean = 6.53, SD = 3.66), median household income in a Florida county (around $60,000 with SD around $25,000), or scores on a state-administered 4th-grade reading assessment (often around 50 with SD around 10), if the data are approximately normal, then about 68% of values fall within ±1 SD of <em>that</em> distribution's mean. The percentages do not change. What changes from one distribution to another is the raw value that corresponds to ±1 SD.</p>
  </div>
