<section class="step">
  <div class="step-header">
    <span class="step-number">6</span>
    <h2>Looking ahead: the Central Limit Theorem</h2>
  </div>
  <p>You have now seen what the normal curve is, when it applies, and how to translate values into Z-scores. Next week, this foundation supports a larger move: using the normal curve to make inferences about populations from samples.</p>
  <p>The key tool is the <strong>Central Limit Theorem (CLT)</strong>, which says that even when the underlying data is not normally distributed, the distribution of <em>repeated sample means</em> drawn from the population of interest becomes approximately normal as the number of samples drawn from the population grows. This is why normal-curve methods can be applied to data like income (right-skewed) or arrest counts (right-skewed and discrete), as long as the analysis is working with means of large samples rather than individual values.</p>
  <p>The CLT is what makes most of inferential statistics possible. We will cover it in detail in Week 5. For now, the takeaway: the normal curve is not just a model for individual data. It is also a model for what happens when you sample from any distribution repeatedly. That bridge from "individual values" to "sample means" is what turns the normal curve from a descriptive tool into an inferential one.</p>
</section>

